  <fr:p>First let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[c\in  C]]></fr:tex> represent <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[F]]></fr:tex>, so that there is a <fr:link
type="local"
href="rs-0010.xml"
addr="rs-0010"
title="Natural isomorphism">natural
  isomorphism</fr:link> <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[C(c, -)\overset {\alpha }{\cong } F]]></fr:tex>. Then the pair <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[(c,   \alpha _c(1_c))]]></fr:tex> is initial in <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\text {el}(F)]]></fr:tex>. Indeed, for any <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[(d, y)\in \text {el}(F)]]></fr:tex>,
  the <fr:link
type="local"
href="rs-000E.xml"
addr="rs-000E"
title="Bijection">bijection</fr:link> <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\alpha _d]]></fr:tex> determines a unique element <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f\in  C(c, d)]]></fr:tex>
  so that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[Ff(\alpha _c(1_c)) = y]]></fr:tex>; this exactly expresses initiality.</fr:p>

  <fr:p>Conversely, let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[(c, x)]]></fr:tex> be initial in <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\text {el}(F)]]></fr:tex>. By the <fr:link
type="local"
href="rs-0014.xml"
addr="rs-0014"
title="Yoneda lemma">Yoneda
  lemma</fr:link>, the element <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[x\in  Fc]]></fr:tex> determines a <fr:link
type="local"
href="rs-000V.xml"
addr="rs-000V"
title="Natural transformation">natural
  transformation</fr:link> <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[C(c, -)\xrightarrow {\Phi (x)} F]]></fr:tex>; we need to show this is an
  isomorphism. Initiality of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[(c, x)]]></fr:tex> asserts that, for any <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[(d, y)\in \text {el}(F)]]></fr:tex>,
  there is a unique map <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[c\xrightarrow {f_y} d]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[Ff_y(x) = y]]></fr:tex>. Now in the
  proof of the Yoneda lemma, <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\Phi (x)]]></fr:tex> was constructed so that
  <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[F(\Phi (x)_d)(f) = Ff(x)]]></fr:tex>, so the assignment <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[(d, y)\mapsto  f_y]]></fr:tex> inverts
  <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\Phi (x)_d]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
